  <h2>HCD Process</h2>
  <p>HCD is a cyclical process that moves between divergent and convergent modes of thinking. Each phase has its cyle: in Discovery, a team diverges through desk research, then converges on a problem frame, and the diverges again when listening to the points of view of the participants. </p>
  <p> In the Design phase, idea generation, or ideation, requires divergent thinking, then convergence around a few viable options to prototype and test. </p>
  <p>Delivery includes divergence around modes of delivery and collaboration with implementation teams, then convergence around an workable model. </p>
  <p>And finally, the Measurement phase also requires divergent creativity as the team and collaborators considers what and when to measure, how to collect it, and how to parse that data, the convergence around a plan. At each stage, the team is aware that a return to a previous stage might be necessary.</p>
  <p>This process is not strictly linear, progressing from one stage to another; it is subject to informed and intentional revision at all points.
  </p>
  <p>By using HCD in our work to improve agency services, we can identify innovations or solutions that are desirable, feasible, and viable. Then we design the solution, launch it, and measure its effectiveness against our initial
    goals. If the solution falls short of those goals, we make revisions based on further feedback from users and test it again. Such dynamism is inherent to the HCD process. HCD solutions are designed to be dynamic and changing because the people and situations for whom we are designing will themselves be dymnamic and subject to change over time.
  </p>
